{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>The voltage-sensitive sodium channel consists of an ion conducting pore forming alpha-subunit regulated by one or more non-pore-forming beta subunits. There are five different beta-subunit proteins (beta-1, beta-1B, beta-2, beta-3, and beta-4) encoded by four genes (SCN1B-SCN4B; beta-1B is a splice variant of SCN1B) [[cite:PUB00096461], [cite:PUB00096467]]. Beta-subunits modulate the kinetics and voltage dependence of the alpha-subunits and they also affect the voltage-gated potassium channels. These subunits participate in nonconducting roles, including cell-cell and cell-matrix adhesion, directing neuronal proliferation, migration, and fasciculation, and modulating the effects of pharmacological compounds on voltage-gated sodium channels, playing important roles in development and disease [[cite:PUB00096467], [cite:PUB00096471]].</p>\n\n<p>Subunit beta-1 is crucial in the assembly, expression, and functional modulation of the sodium channel that can modulate multiple alpha subunit isoforms from brain, skeletal muscle, and heart [[cite:PUB00062899], [cite:PUB00062900]]. Both beta-1 and beta-3 associate with neurofascin through their extracellular immunoglobulin-like domains. This association may target the sodium channels to the nodes of Ranvier of developing axons and retain these channels at the nodes in mature myelinated axons [[cite:PUB00062896]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR013783", "name" "Immunoglobulin-like fold", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR10546" "SODIUM CHANNEL SUBUNIT BETA-1 AND 3"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Sodium channel subunit beta-1/beta-3", "short" "Na_channel_b1/b3"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 37, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 631, "taxa" 2145, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions"